'''Lance Bouma''' (born March 25, 1990) is a [[Canada|Canadian]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[centre (ice hockey)|centre]] for the [[Abbotsford Heat]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL). He is a prospect of the [[Calgary Flames]], drafted as their third round selection, 78th overall, in the [[2008 NHL Entry Draft]] and made his NHL debut in January 2011. As a junior, he was a member of the [[Vancouver Giants]] team that won the [[2007 Memorial Cup]].

==Playing career==
Bouma was a second round selection of the [[Vancouver Giants]] at the 2005 [[Western Hockey League]] (WHL) Bantam Draft.<ref>{{Cite book|editor=Flett, Cory and Watts, Jessie|title=2009<U+2013>10 WHL Guide|publisher=Western Hockey League|page=140}}</ref> He spent the majority of the 2005<U+2013>06 season playing [[minor hockey|midget hockey]] in the Rural Alberta Midget Hockey League, but appeared in five games as a 15-year-old for the Giants, scoring one goal and four points.<ref name="FlamesPC">{{cite web |url=http://flames.nhl.com/club/player.htm?id=8474642&view=stats |title=Lance Bouma player card |publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref> He became a regular for the Giants in the [[2006<U+2013>07 WHL season]], appearing in 49 regular season games and 22 playoff games as the Giants reached the WHL final. Though the team lost to the [[Medicine Hat Tigers]] for the league championship, they qualified for the [[2007 Memorial Cup]] as the host team, and defeated the Tigers in the final for the [[Canadian Hockey League]] championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mastercardmemorialcup.com/page/the-2007-memorial-cup-history |title=2007 Memorial Cup History |publisher=Canadian Hockey League |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref> Bouma finished second on his team in rookie playoff scoring behind [[James Wright (ice hockey)|James Wright]]. Additionally, he played for Team Alberta at the [[2007 Canada Games]] hockey tournament, scoring two goals as the team finished in fourth place.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/draftprospectdetail.htm?dpid=68&tab=prf |title=Lance Bouma draft prospect card |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref> 

After improving to 12 goals and 35 points in 71 games for the Giants in [[2007<U+2013>08 WHL season|2007<U+2013>08]], Bouma was selected by the [[Calgary Flames]] in the third round, 78th overall, of the [[2008 NHL Entry Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/victoriatimescolonist/news/sports/story.html?id=15409045-a42f-4bda-8e73-49f16b04645b |title=Draft notebook |work=Victoria Times-Columnist |date=2008-06-22 |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref> He remained in junior for two more seasons, and served as the Giants' captain in [[2009<U+2013>10 WHL season|2009<U+2013>10]], in which the team reached the third round of the WHL playoffs before bowing out to the [[Tri-City Americans]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tsn.ca/chl/story/?id=319491 |title=Tri-City down Vancouver to reach first ever WHL final |publisher=The Sports Network |date=2010-04-26 |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref> Upon elimination, Bouma played his first professional games, joining the Flames' AHL affiliate, the [[Abbotsford Heat]], for five playoff games.<ref name="FlamesPC" /> He scored one goal, against the [[Hamilton Bulldogs]] in the second round of the AHL playoffs.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gaffar |first=Ifraan |url=http://www.news1130.com/news/local/article/52309--the-heat-win-in-the-valley |title=The Heat win in the valley |publisher=News1130 |date=2010-05-07 |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref>

Bouma joined the Heat full time for the [[2010<U+2013>11 AHL season]], and with 11 goals through his first 49 games, was approaching his best career best goal total at any level.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tucker |first=Cam |url=http://www.abbotsfordtimes.com/sports/Lance+Bouma+jumps+from+Heat+Flames/4223928/story.html |title=Lance Bouma jumps from Heat to Flames |work=Abbotsford Times |date=2011-02-04 |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref> Not known for his offence, Bouma relies on his physical play and willingness to drive the net, qualities that earned him his first recall to the NHL on February 3, 2011, when he was assigned to join the Flames.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tucker |first=Cam |url=http://www.abbotsfordtimes.com/dream+come+true+Abbotsford+Heat+Lance+Bouma/4221022/story.html |title="A dream come true" for Abbotsford Heat<U+2019>s Lance Bouma |work=Abbotsford Times |date=2011-02-04 |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref> He made his NHL debut two nights later against the [[Los Angeles Kings]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Cruickshank |first=Scott |url=http://www.calgaryherald.com/sports/hockey/calgary-flames/Bouma+finds+debut+memories+last+lifetime/4231897/story.html |title=Bouma finds debut memories last a lifetime |work=Calgary Herald |date=2011-02-06 |accessdate=2011-02-06}}</ref> and scored his first point, assisting on a [[Mikael Backlund]] goal, on February 7 against the [[Chicago Blackhawks]].<ref>{{cite web |last=MacFarlane |first=Steve |url=http://www.calgarysun.com/sports/myflames/2011/02/07/17190371.html |title=Flames into playoff berth |work=Calgary Sun |date=2011-02-08 |accessdate=2011-02-08}}</ref>

He scored his first NHL goal on January 7, 2012 against [[Niklas B<U+00E4>ckstr<U+00F6>m]] of the [[Minnesota Wild]] in a 3-1 victory.

